  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is a real and deeply felt issue, especially for women and people of color, who often carry the weight of historical and societal biases. Growing up in Chicago as an immigrant child of a working-class mother and a doctor who was a role model, I’ve seen firsthand how these stereotypes can affect young minds. When a girl sees a teacher or a classmate say something like, 'You’re not cut out for engineering,' it doesn’t just hurt—it can make her question her own abilities. I remember my own experience in high school when I was told by a teacher that I wasn’t 'the type' to excel in math, and that belief lingered long after. This isn’t just about individual discouragement; it’s about systemic issues that have been passed down through generations. We must address stereotype threat not by simply telling people to 'be confident,' but by creating environments where everyone feels seen and valued. In my community, I’ve worked with local schools to introduce mentorship programs that connect students with professionals who share their backgrounds. It’s important to acknowledge the roots of these stereotypes and to build bridges, not walls. As a creative person who loves gardening and cooking, I know that growth happens when we nurture the right conditions—just like plants need sunlight and water. We can’t ignore this issue because it affects the future of our communities. Let’s create spaces where every child feels they belong and can thrive in STEM without fear.",
